<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="9258b634-ee83-58f7-b380-7cf30f4dc71c" activityNameId="508835ce-ac53-4df7-9289-8324ce58e170" parentActivityId="96042d24-3959-453e-9a8b-e0e9b1bd892b" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">butadiene purification, extractive distillation of crude butadiene</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">extractive distillation</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts with the raw materials entering the purification process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with butadiene being ready for further processing or transportation at the production site gate. The dataset includes the input materials, energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This process describes the purification of crude butadiene from steam cracking to 1 kg of pure butadiene by extractive distillation,</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Butadiene cannot be separated from this C4 hydrocarbon mixture by simple distillation, because 1,3-butadiene and butane form an azeotrope. The method of choice for the isolation of butadiene from C4 fractions is extractive distillation with selective organic solvents. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Grub, J.; Löser, E. (2011): Butadiene, Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Wiley-VCH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">IFEU/PlasticsEurope (2021): Eco-profile of Steam Cracker Products: Ethylene, Propylene, Butadiene, Pyrolysis Gasoline, Ethylene Oxide (EO), Ethylene Glycols (MEG, DEG, TEG)</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0723d252-7e2a-11de-9820-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RER</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Representativeness estimated for min. 80 % of European (EU + GB, NO, CH) production.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Butadiene cannot be separated from the C4 hydrocarbon mixture leaving the steam cracker by simple distillation, since butadiene and butane form an azeotrope. The most applied methods are liquid-liquid extraction and extractive distillation.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The method of choice for this dataset is isolation of butadiene by extractive distillation with N-methylpyrrolidone as a solvent (BASF-NMP). </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">The process consists of four subprocesses, C3 predistillation, extractive distillation, degassing and butadiene distillation,</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">In the C3 predistillation, the more unsaturated hydrocarbons, e.g. acetylenes and diolefins, are dissolved in NMP, whilst the butenes/butanes are removed from the top of the washer. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">In the extractive distillation step, the C4 acetylenes and part of the 1,2-butadiene are removed from the bottom of the tower. This is possible since these substances are more soluble in NMP than 1,3-butadiene. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">The 1,3-butadiene is removed from the top of the tower and is separated from the additional compounds (propyne and C5 hydrocarbons) by degasing</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">In a final step, the 1,3-butadiene is distilled.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Grub, J.; Löser, E. (2011): Butadiene, Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Wiley-VCH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">IFEU/PlasticsEurope (2021): Eco-profile of Steam Cracker Products: Ethylene, Propylene, Butadiene, Pyrolysis Gasoline, Ethylene Oxide (EO), Ethylene Glycols (MEG, DEG, TEG)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">BASF: BASF Butadiene Extraction Technology, available here: https://www.basf.com/cn/en/products/chemicals/Intermediates/solutions/butadiene-extraction.html#accordion_v2-2f5da26453-item-eb411fc36e, last accessed 03-02-2023.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2019-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Data collection 2019/2020. The technology is not expected to change within 5 years.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
